04440nam a22006615i 9780271086835DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20212020pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710868357 a10.1515/97802710868352doi  a(DE-B1597)583785  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aBC185b.F74 2020 7aLAN0150002bisacsh04a808.009382231 aFredal, James, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Enthymeme :bSyllogism, Reasoning, and Narrative in Ancient Greek Rhetoric /cJames Fredal. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2020  a1 online resource (226 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tPart One 3.0 -- t1. Enthymeme 3.0 -- t2. 3.0 and Its Problems -- tPart Two 2.0 -- t3. Aristotle, Sullogismos, and 2.0 -- t4. 2.0 and Its Problems -- tPart Three 1.0 -- t5 Enthymizing in the Orators -- t6 Oratorical Enthymizing in Context -- t7 Enthymizing and Adversarial Narratives -- tPart Four Lysias and the Enthymeme -- t8. Enthymizing in Lysias 1, On the Death of Eratosthenes -- t9. A Many-Layered Tale -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCentral to rhetorical theory, the enthymeme is most often defined as a truncated syllogism. Suppressing a premise that the audience already knows, this rhetorical device relies on the audience to fill in the missing information, thereby making the argument more persuasive. James Fredal argues that this view of the enthymeme is wrong. Presenting a new exegesis of Aristotle and classic texts of Attic oratory, Fredal shows that the standard reading of Aristotle's enthymeme is inaccurate-and that Aristotle himself distorts what enthymemes are and how they work.From close analysis of the Rhetoric, Topics, and Analytics, Fredal finds that Aristotle's enthymeme is, in fact, not syllogistic and is different from the enthymeme as it was used by Attic orators such as Lysias and Isaeus. Fredal argues that the enthymeme, as it was originally understood and used, is a technique of storytelling, primarily forensic storytelling, aimed at eliciting from the audience an inference about a narrative. According to Fredal, narrative rather than formal logic is the seedbed of the enthymeme and of rhetoric more broadly.The Enthymeme reassesses a fundamental doctrine of rhetorical instruction, clarifies the viewpoints of the tradition, and presents a new form of rhetoric for further study and use. This groundbreaking book will be welcomed by scholars and students of classical rhetoric, the history of rhetoric, and rhetorical theory as well as communications studies, classical studies, and classical philosophy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aElectronic books. 0aEnthymeme (Logic). 0aNarration (Rhetoric). 0aRhetoric, Ancient. 0aSyllogism. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Rhetoric.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311074521440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271086835zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271086835423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271086835.jpg  a978-3-11-074521-4  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aEBA_CL_LS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK